Latency = how fast one request is
Throughput = how many requests you handle over time

You can have low latency but low throughput (fast but can’t handle many users)
Or high throughput but high latency (handles many users but each is slow)


Vertical Scaling (scale up)
Increase power of a single machine: + CPU + RAM

Horizontal Scaling (scale out)
Add more machines

Basically: Distributed system are necessary when you reach a point where:
    .A single machine becomes too expansive
    .Or becomes a reliability risk

Java example:

ThreadPoolExecutor executor =
    new ThreadPoolExecutor(
        4, 8,
        60, TimeUnit.SECONDS,
        new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(100),
        new ThreadPoolExecutor.CallerRunsPolicy()
    );

4 = default pool size
8 = maximum pool size
60 + Timeunit = Time a extra thread keeps alive after idle
ArrayBlockingQueue = essencially the buffer, where the tasks wait when core threads are busy
CallerRunsPolicy = What happens when all 8 threads are busy and queue size is 100

The core idea is: The bigger the queue is, the fewer the rejection but slows the response
    - Big queue = +latency -throughtput
